To validate for all roles matching you need to invert the search:
```
Set&lt;String&gt; roles= Set.of(roleArray);

boolean hasRole = true;
for (UserRoles role : UserRoles.values()) {
  if (!roles.contains(role.name())) {
    hasRole = false;
    break;
  }
}
```
A small improvement is that you can use `Set` instead of `List` for the search - it won&#39;t really make a difference for such small data set, but for search only operations, as in your case, it&#39;s the correct data structure.

First, I suggest some changes to your `enum` class: 
 
 - I made the name of the class singular, not plural. For example, if you wanted to use `enum` to represent the days of the week, you might use `enum DayOfWeek`, not `DaysOfWeek`. I find it is less confusing that way.
 - I completed the code for the constructor.
 - I added a `boolean isMatch (String )` method.

````
enum UserRole {
    ROLE_ADMIN(&quot;ROLE_ADMIN&quot;),
    ROLE_CONFIG_EDITOR(&quot;ROLE_CONFIG_EDITOR&quot;),
    ROLE_USER(&quot;ROLE_USER&quot;);
    private final String roleName;

    UserRole (String roleName) {
        this.roleName = roleName;
    }
    
    public boolean isMatch (String roleName) { 
        return this.roleName.equalsIgnoreCase(roleName);
    }
}
````

Now, if I understand the problem correctly, for each user, you will have an array of roles of that user, as a `List&lt;String&gt;`. You want to find out if each element in that array is a valid role.

Given a `String []` of roles for a single user, this code will return `true` if each element is a valid role, and return `false` if any element is not valid. This is an &quot;old dog&quot; approach.
````
 public static boolean enumTest (List&lt;String&gt; rolesOfThisUser) { 
  
    final UserRole [] userRoles = UserRole.values();
    boolean allRolesValid = true;
    for (String singleRole: rolesOfThisUser)  { 
        boolean thisRoleValid = false;
       for (UserRole test: userRoles) {
           thisRoleValid = thisRoleValid || test.isMatch(singleRole);
       }
       allRolesValid = allRolesValid &amp;&amp; thisRoleValid;
    } 
    return allRolesValid;
}
````
Note that it will return `true` if the argument is an empty array. This is an example of &quot;vacuously true&quot;.

Test: 

````
System.out.println (enumTest (Arrays.asList 
    (new String [] {&quot;ROLE_user&quot;,&quot;WRONG_ROLE&quot;})));
System.out.println (enumTest (Arrays.asList 
    (new String [] {&quot;ROLE_admin&quot;, &quot;role_CONFIG_EDITOR&quot;})));
System.out.println (enumTest (Arrays.asList
    (new String [] {})));
````
Output:
````
false
true
true
````
Note that there will be exactly one instance of each value of an `enum`. If Pat and Chris are each an administrator, they will have the *same instance* of `ROLE_ADMIN`.

